column23: Hog Hole (Allan H. Treman State Marine Park)

column46: Small movement of Long-tailed Ducks,Bufflehead, and Common Goldeneye flying upstream (SW).  I''ve noted similar movement of birds along the St. Lawrence River during migration when the winds were right (downstream in spring, upstream in fall), but these movements have always been modest.
column47: Flying upstream.  I first saw it in my binoculars and noted the relatively long wings and the erratic and twisty flight.  I quickly got it in my scope and saw it best from behind as it flew away from me.  The wing bars were fairly bold and broadest on the inner wing; there was no black on the leading edge of the wing, as a Sanderling would show.  The back was a farily uniform pale gray without any stripes, braces, or other noticeable markings.  I ruled out Sanderling based on the wing pattern, and the flight also was more typical of phalaropes.  I ruled out Red-necked Phalarope based on the relatively uniform pale gray of the back.

column23: Hog Hole (Allan H. Treman State Marine Park)
column46: A very nice day. Mostly clear. Calm. I was hoping for Purple Sandpiper, given the large number along Lake Ontario, but no luck. column23: Hamlin Beach SP--Parking Lot No. 4 (Primary Lakewatch site)
column46: Cloudy day, with temperatures heading from about 50 to nearly 70 degrees F. Cave swallows were expected.--   Andy Guthrie was there for much of the early time, then many arrived. Dave and Mike Tetlow watched from a short ways west where you can see both inland and over the lake, but lake the shelter from the wind. They had the first 2 CASW about 9:45. After that we all moved out there and about 10:30 had 5 more CASW close by that would have passed right above the lakewatch site. At 11:17 another passed right over us.--   I had to leave , but several stayed and later Andy came back. By 1:30 the total was 47 CASW and by 3:15 73 (posted earlier by Andy and Dave). Many of the birds passed inland back by the parkloop roads.--   Early the wind was S. Later, stronger and sw to wsw.

column23: Salt Marsh Nature Center at Marine Park
column46: Ranger Sergeant Tony and Ranger John led the group through the area undergoing restoration and we continued along the edge of the golf course. A chill west wind made the sunny morning feel wintry, but what an assortment of birds! Long-absent waterfowl returned for the season (welcome back, Buffleheads); Pine Siskins, rarely seen by our group, flew by in a surprisingly large flock (and we learned their call); additional species seemed to appear with almost every step.

column23: Salt Marsh Nature Center at Marine Park
column46: Ranger Christina led us through the new section on a truly glorious morning.  Bright hazy sun, no wind, mild temperatures - all helped us appreciate the site with a particularly high tide. Lots of ducks and geese paddling around among the new grasses. Highlights: wonderful views of a perched Red-tailed Hawk as well as action shots of it being bombed by a Kestrel, and later taking the initiative to drive off crows that looked threatening; lots of Buffleheads stirring up the water; more species of Sparrow than usually seen at this site - Song, White-throated, Savannah, Fox, and Swamp; a "standoff" between a Kestrel and a Mourning Dove, as they stood a foot apart on a rock eyeing each other; and a "fleet" of Red-breasted Mergansers swimming and diving like a chorus line.

Decided to bird Hard's Lake as I never really check this location but it's always in the back of mind. In the last couple of weeks, I've noticed an increase in ducks, gulls, and geese on the lake while driving by on Sunrise Highway. The park has finally re opened since the hurricane and access to the west side of the lake is open.

column23: Salt Marsh Nature Center at Marine Park--Southwest
column46: In contrast to dismal weather forecasts, it was a beautiful warm and sunny morning on the West side of the creek, filled with the sights, sounds, scents, and activities of spring.  Birdsong, especially of Yellow Warblers, Red-Winged Blackbirds, and Northern Cardinals, filled the air, as did the heady scent of Autumn Olive blooms. Gorgeous Baltimore Oriole males seemed to be everywhere, some gathering nesting materials, and at least one cardinal chick was seen, hopping around its nest, under the watchful eye of Mom & Dad.  Special treats were our reunion with the Gerrittsen kildeer and the appearance of many butterflies, including Common Buckeyes, American Ladies, Red Admirals, and an extraordinary number of Eastern Tailed Blues, all posing for Mohammed''s camera.  Speaking of reunions, we were pleased to have Tom, on morning leave from baby Charlie, joining us on our walk, and finding us "good birds."
